defs.docs: Utilities for random number generation

defs.name: distributions
defs.docs: Generating random samples from probability distributions.

defs.name: uniform
defs.docs: A distribution uniformly sampling numbers within a given range.

defs.name: Uniform
defs.docs: Sample values uniformly between two bounds.

defs.name: new
defs.value: fn <B1, B2> (low: B1, high: B2) -> Uniform<X>
defs.docs:
Create a new `Uniform` instance which samples uniformly from the half
 open range `[low, high)` (excluding `high`). Panics if `low >= high`.

defs.name: new_inclusive
defs.value: fn <B1, B2> (low: B1, high: B2) -> Uniform<X>
defs.docs:
Create a new `Uniform` instance which samples uniformly from the closed
 range `[low, high]` (inclusive). Panics if `low > high`.

defs.name: SampleUniform
defs.docs:
Helper trait for creating objects using the correct implementation of
 [`UniformSampler`] for the sampling type.

defs.name: Sampler
defs.docs: The `UniformSampler` implementation supporting type `X`.

defs.name: UniformSampler
defs.docs: Helper trait handling actual uniform sampling.

defs.name: X
defs.docs: The type sampled by this implementation.

defs.value: fn <B1, B2> (low: B1, high: B2) -> Self

defs.name: new_inclusive
defs.value: fn <B1, B2> (low: B1, high: B2) -> Self
defs.docs: Construct self, with inclusive bounds `[low, high]`.

defs.name: sample
defs.docs: Sample a value.

defs.name: sample_single
defs.value: fn <R, B1, B2> (low: B1, high: B2, rng: &mut R) -> Self::X

Helper trait similar to [`Borrow`] but implemented

defs.name: borrow

defs.name: Bernoulli
defs.docs: The Bernoulli distribution.

defs.name: new
defs.docs: Construct a new `Bernoulli` with the given probability of success `p`.

defs.name: from_ratio
defs.docs:
Construct a new `Bernoulli` with the probability of success of
 `numerator`-in-`denominator`. I.e. `new_ratio(2, 3)` will return
 a `Bernoulli` with a 2-in-3 chance, or about 67%, of returning `true`.

defs.name: WeightedIndex
defs.docs:
A distribution using weighted sampling to pick a discretely selected
 item.

defs.name: new
defs.docs:
Creates a new a `WeightedIndex` [`Distribution`] using the values
 in `weights`. The weights can use any type `X` for which an
 implementation of [`Uniform<X>`] exists.

defs.name: NoItem
defs.docs: The provided iterator contained no items.

defs.name: NegativeWeight
defs.docs: A weight lower than zero was used.

defs.name: AllWeightsZero
defs.docs: All items in the provided iterator had a weight of zero.

defs.name: WeightedError
defs.docs: Error type returned from `WeightedIndex::new`.

defs.name: UnitSphereSurface
defs.docs: Samples uniformly from the surface of the unit sphere in three dimensions.

defs.name: new
defs.docs: Construct a new `UnitSphereSurface` distribution.

defs.name: UnitCircle
defs.docs: Samples uniformly from the edge of the unit circle in two dimensions.

defs.name: new
defs.docs: Construct a new `UnitCircle` distribution.

defs.name: Gamma
defs.docs: The Gamma distribution `Gamma(shape, scale)` distribution.

defs.name: ChiSquared
defs.docs:
The chi-squared distribution `χ²(k)`, where `k` is the degrees of

Create a new chi-squared distribution with degrees-of-freedom

defs.name: FisherF
defs.docs: The Fisher F distribution `F(m, n)`.

defs.name: new

Create a new `FisherF` distribution, with the given

defs.name: StudentT
defs.docs:
The Student t distribution, `t(nu)`, where `nu` is the degrees of

defs.name: new
defs.docs:
Create a new Student t distribution with `n` degrees of
 freedom. Panics if `n <= 0`.

defs.name: Beta
defs.docs: The Beta distribution with shape parameters `alpha` and `beta`.

defs.name: new
defs.docs:
Construct an object representing the `Beta(alpha, beta)`

defs.name: StandardNormal
defs.docs:
Samples floating-point numbers according to the normal distribution
 `N(0, 1)` (a.k.a. a standard normal, or Gaussian). This is equivalent to
 `Normal::new(0.0, 1.0)` but faster.

defs.name: Normal
defs.docs: The normal distribution `N(mean, std_dev**2)`.

defs.name: new
defs.docs:
Construct a new `Normal` distribution with the given mean and
 standard deviation.

defs.name: LogNormal
defs.docs: The log-normal distribution `ln N(mean, std_dev**2)`.

defs.name: new
defs.docs:
Construct a new `LogNormal` distribution with the given mean
 and standard deviation.

defs.name: Exp1
defs.docs:
Samples floating-point numbers according to the exponential distribution,
 with rate parameter `λ = 1`. This is equivalent to `Exp::new(1.0)` or
 sampling with `-rng.gen::<f64>().ln()`, but faster.

defs.name: Exp
defs.docs: The exponential distribution `Exp(lambda)`.

defs.name: new
defs.docs:
Construct a new `Exp` with the given shape parameter
 `lambda`. Panics if `lambda <= 0`.

defs.name: Pareto
defs.docs: Samples floating-point numbers according to the Pareto distribution

defs.name: new
defs.docs: Construct a new Pareto distribution with given `scale` and `shape`.

defs.name: Poisson
defs.docs: The Poisson distribution `Poisson(lambda)`.

defs.name: new
defs.docs:
Construct a new `Poisson` with the given shape parameter
 `lambda`. Panics if `lambda <= 0`.

defs.name: Binomial
defs.docs: The binomial distribution `Binomial(n, p)`.

defs.name: new
defs.docs:
Construct a new `Binomial` with the given shape parameters `n` (number

defs.name: Cauchy
defs.docs: The Cauchy distribution `Cauchy(median, scale)`.

defs.name: new
defs.docs:
Construct a new `Cauchy` with the given shape parameters

defs.name: Dirichlet
defs.docs: The dirichelet distribution `Dirichlet(alpha)`.

defs.name: new_with_param

defs.name: OpenClosed01
defs.docs:
A distribution to sample floating point numbers uniformly in the half-open
 interval `(0, 1]`, i.e. including 1 but not 0.

defs.name: Open01
defs.docs:
A distribution to sample floating point numbers uniformly in the open

defs.name: Alphanumeric
defs.docs:
Sample a `char`, uniformly distributed over ASCII letters and numbers:
 a-z, A-Z and 0-9.

defs.name: Standard
defs.docs:
A generic random value distribution, implemented for many primitive types.
 Usually generates values with a numerically uniform distribution, and with a
 range appropriate to the type.

defs.name: EntropyRng
defs.docs:
An interface returning random data from external source(s), provided

defs.name: StepRng
new
defs.docs:
Create a `StepRng`, yielding an arithmetic sequence starting with
 `initial` and incremented by `increment` each time.

defs.name: SmallRng
defs.docs:
An RNG recommended when small state, cheap initialization and good
 performance are required. The PRNG algorithm in `SmallRng` is chosen to be
 efficient on the current platform, **without consideration for cryptography
 or security**. The size of its state is much smaller than for [`StdRng`].

defs.name: StdRng
defs.docs:
The standard RNG. The PRNG algorithm in `StdRng` is chosen to be efficient
 on the current platform, to be statistically strong and unpredictable
 (meaning a cryptographically secure PRNG).

defs.name: ThreadRng
defs.docs:
The type returned by [`thread_rng`], essentially just a reference to the
 PRNG in thread-local memory.

defs.name: thread_rng
defs.docs:
Retrieve the lazily-initialized thread-local random number generator,
 seeded by the system. Intended to be used in method chaining style,
 e.g. `thread_rng().gen::<i32>()`, or cached locally, e.g.
 `let mut rng = thread_rng();`.  Invoked by the `Default` trait, making
 `ThreadRng::default()` equivelent.

defs.name: SliceRandom
defs.docs:
Extension trait on slices, providing random mutation and sampling methods.
 
 An implementation is provided for slices. This may also be implementable for
 other types.

defs.name: Item
defs.docs: The element type.

defs.name: choose
defs.docs:
Returns a reference to one random element of the slice, or `None` if the
 slice is empty.
 
 Depending on the implementation, complexity is expected to be `O(1)`.

defs.name: choose_mut
defs.value: fn <R> (&mut self, rng: &mut R) -> Option<&mut Self::Item>
defs.docs:
Returns a mutable reference to one random element of the slice, or
 `None` if the slice is empty.
 
 Depending on the implementation, complexity is expected to be `O(1)`.

defs.name: choose_multiple
defs.value: fn <R> (&self, rng: &mut R, amount: usize) -> SliceChooseIter<Self, Self::Item>

defs.name: choose_weighted
defs.value: fn <R, F, B, X> (&self, rng: &mut R, weight: F) -> Result<&Self::Item, WeightedError>
defs.docs:
Similar to [`choose`], where the likelihood of each outcome may be
 specified. The specified function `weight` maps items `x` to a relative
 likelihood `weight(x)`. The probability of each item being selected is
 therefore `weight(x) / s`, where `s` is the sum of all `weight(x)`.

defs.name: choose_weighted_mut
defs.value: fn <R, F, B, X> (&mut self, rng: &mut R, weight: F) -> Result<&mut Self::Item, WeightedError>
defs.docs:
Similar to [`choose_mut`], where the likelihood of each outcome may be
 specified. The specified function `weight` maps items `x` to a relative
 likelihood `weight(x)`. The probability of each item being selected is
 therefore `weight(x) / s`, where `s` is the sum of all `weight(x)`.

defs.name: shuffle
defs.docs:
Shuffle a mutable slice in place.
 
 Depending on the implementation, complexity is expected to be `O(1)`.

defs.name: partial_shuffle
defs.value: fn <R> (&mut self, rng: &mut R, amount: usize) -> (&mut [Self::Item], &mut [Self::Item])
defs.docs: Shuffle a slice in place, but exit early.

defs.name: IteratorRandom
defs.docs: Extension trait on iterators, providing random sampling methods.

defs.name: choose
defs.docs:
Choose one element at random from the iterator. If you have a slice,
 it's significantly faster to call the [`choose`] or [`choose_mut`]
 functions using the slice instead.

defs.name: choose_multiple_fill
defs.value: fn <R> (mut self, rng: &mut R, buf: &mut [Self::Item]) -> usize
defs.docs:
Collects `amount` values at random from the iterator into a supplied
 buffer.
 
 Although the elements are selected randomly, the order of elements in
 the buffer is neither stable nor fully random. If random ordering is
 desired, shuffle the result.
 
 Returns the number of elements added to the buffer. This equals `amount`
 unless the iterator contains insufficient elements, in which case this
 equals the number of elements available.
 
 Complexity is `O(n)` where `n` is the length of the iterator.

defs.docs: Collects `amount` values at random from the iterator into a vector.

defs.name: fill
defs.docs:
Fill `dest` entirely with random bytes (uniform value distribution),
 where `dest` is any type supporting [`AsByteSliceMut`], namely slices
 and arrays over primitive integer types (`i8`, `i16`, `u32`, etc.).

defs.name: try_fill
defs.value: fn <T> (&mut self, dest: &mut T) -> Result<(), Error>
defs.docs:
Fill `dest` entirely with random bytes (uniform value distribution),
 where `dest` is any type supporting [`AsByteSliceMut`], namely slices
 and arrays over primitive integer types (`i8`, `i16`, `u32`, etc.).

defs.name: gen_bool
defs.docs: Return a bool with a probability `p` of being true.

defs.name: gen_ratio
defs.value: fn (&mut self, numerator: u32, denominator: u32) -> bool
defs.docs:
Return a bool with a probability of `numerator/denominator` of being
 true. I.e. `gen_ratio(2, 3)` has chance of 2 in 3, or about 67%, of
 returning true. If `numerator == denominator`, then the returned value
 is guaranteed to be `true`. If `numerator == 0`, then the returned
 value is guaranteed to be `false`.
